node.text:
After being rejected by their male literary peers, women writers of New York City joined forces to create their own club in 1868 called Sorosis — where men weren't allowed. Sorosis became such a phenomenon that even men applied to join its ranks. They were rejected with the following statement:⁠
⁠
"We willingly admit, of course, that the accident of your sex is on your part a misfortune and not a fault; nor do we wish to arrogate anything to ourselves, because we had the good fortune to be born women... Sorosis is too young for the society of gentlemen and must be allowed time to grow... But for years to come its reply to all male suitors must be, 'Principles, not men.'"⁠
⁠
To learn more about this exclusive women's club, click the link in our bio.⁠
⁠
⁠
⁠

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by History Uncovered on July 27, 2021. May be a drawing of 1 person.

node.text:
Although matchstick making sounds like a simple job, the consequences of working around the materials that were needed to make them were truly devastating.⁠
⁠
Matchsticks were made in factories by women and children who labored for 12 to 16 hours a day, and the process involved dipping the wood matchsticks into a phosphorous solution. The problem with the job was that too much exposure to phosphorus carried a risk specific to matchstick makers: phossy jaw.⁠
⁠
Essentially, phossy jaw was a physical ailment that causes the jaw bone to rot. The disease was known to spread to the brain and cause a very painful death unless the jaw was removed. Even with jaw removal, these factory workers still weren’t guaranteed to survive.⁠
⁠
Follow the link in our profile to read more about some of history's worst jobs.⁠
⁠
⁠

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by History Uncovered in Crete. May be an image of text that says 'The 4,000 Old Code On The Ancient Greek Phaistos Disc Has Just Been Cracked'.

node.text:
In 1908, Italian archaeologist Luigi Pernier was exploring the 4,000-year-old Minoan palace of Phaistos on the island of Crete. After venturing into its subterranean temple, he sifted through dust, ashes, and burned human bones before happening upon a clay disk covered in strange hieroglyphs.⁠
⁠
Just 15 centimeters in diameter, the Phaistos Disc contained a mysterious code that features 240 characters made up of 45 different symbols — none of which belong to any known alphabet. Not only was the language unknown, but experts have never found another artifact that features these same bizarre symbols.⁠
⁠
For more than a century since, the case of the Phaistos Disc has gone unsolved — until now. After devoting 30 years of his life to studying the disc, one intrepid linguist has finally solved this Bronze Age puzzle — read more at the link in our bio.⁠
⁠
⁠

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by History Uncovered in Inyo County, California. May be an image of tree and nature.

node.text:
In the summer of 1957, dendrochronologist Edmund Schulman stumbled upon a small grove of ancient trees in the Inyo Valley in eastern California. All of them were upwards of 4,000 years old, but one in particular stood out: a tree that clocked in at 4,789 years old, making it the oldest tree on Earth.⁠
⁠
Schulman dubbed it the Methuselah tree in honor of the grandfather of the Ark-building Noah, who was said to have lived to be 969 years old. Now the tree had a name, but its location has remained a secret for decades in the interest of protecting this ancient conifer and those surrounding it. To learn more about the oldest tree known to man, visit the link in our bio.⁠
⁠
⁠

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by History Uncovered in Australia.

node.text:
"All my son wanted to do was to see the world. He had itchy feet. His determination to see how the rest of the world lives has cost him his life."⁠
⁠
Just months before 14-year-old Keith Sapsford fell to his death from a plane in 1970, his father had warned him against becoming a stowaway. Charles Sapsford knew his son was constantly looking for adventure and even warned him about a stowaway who had died on a plane.⁠
⁠
But tragically, his son couldn't contain his urge to fly away and soon met the same fate — and a photographer accidentally captured his fatal fall. Read the rest of the tragic story by visiting the link in our profile.⁠
⁠
⁠

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by History Uncovered in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania. May be an image of one or more people and indoor.

node.text:
A rare copy of the Declaration of Independence dating back 200 years has just been uncovered in Philadelphia. The copy is from the first engraving printing from the original Declaration that was commissioned in 1820 when politicians realized they needed facsimile copies to use for everyday work.⁠
⁠
By then, the original handwritten copy was becoming increasingly fragile. It is only the eighth ever discovered printed on paper from this original copy run and will now be displayed at the American Philosophical Society near Liberty Hall — click the link in our bio to read more.⁠
⁠
⁠
#declarationofindependence #ushistory #americanhistory #discoveries #libertyhall

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by History Uncovered in Washington D.C.. May be an image of 1 person.

node.text:
President James Buchanan was known for his signature drink — Madeira wine. The drink gets its name from the Portuguese island where it’s grown and bottled, once an important stop for cargo ships between Europe and the Americas. The wine was fortified with brandy to allow it to survive the journey (a quality the president perhaps hoped to absorb) and would ripen and mature as the boats passed through the extremes of heat and cold, taking on a rich flavor.⁠
⁠
Buchanan famously enjoyed the drink so much that his adversary William Forney said, "The Madeira and sherry [Buchanan] has consumed would fill more than one cellar and the rye whiskey that he has 'punished' would make Jacob Baer's heart glad…"⁠
⁠
To learn more about the aggressive drinking habits of America's 15th President, visit the link in our profile. ⁠
⁠
⁠

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by History Uncovered on July 24, 2021. May be an image of 1 person and text that says 'At 77, Morgan Freeman Became A First-Time Time Beekeeper And Turned His Ranch Into A 124-Acre Sanctuary'.

node.text:
Morgan Freeman is concerned about the bees — so much so that in 2014 he added a honey bee sanctuary to his 124-acre Mississippi ranch, complete with 26 beehives imported from Arkansas. In order to adapt them to a new climate and flora, he had to initially feed them a strict diet of sugar water before learning what species of plants and flowers they preferred. Go inside this incredibly charming tale by clicking the link in our profile.⁠
⁠
⁠

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by History Uncovered in Florida.

node.text:
In the 16th century, the Church of Nuestra Seño de la Remedios stood in St. Augustine, Florida, and members would be buried beneath the sacred grounds after they passed away. The church no longer exists, but a wine shop is now located on the premises — and the owner just discovered the remains of bodies below his floorboards. ⁠
⁠
Well-preserved within the untouched soil, archaeologists have uncovered seven people, likely to have died between 1572 and 1586. Learn more about this unexpected discovery of America's first colonists by following the link in our bio.⁠
⁠
⁠
#historynews #staugustine #discoveries #florida #americanhistory #colonialhistory

node.text:
In Prohibition-era America, Ma Barker ran a family business of bank robbery, kidnapping, and murder. The Midwestern mother of four oversaw her sons organize the Barker-Karpis gang, who regularly shot policemen and held wealthy men for ransom.⁠
⁠
But after the new technique of fingerprinting identified several members of the gang, their empire began to crumble. Click the link in our profile to learn how the Barker’s middle-aged matriarch became the face of their criminal enterprise.⁠

node.text:
When Nathaniel Bar-Jonah was sentenced to 130 years in prison for child molestation charges, his neighbors in Great Falls, Montana started to reassess his behavior over the years. One remembered that her young son always acted "angry and withdrawn" after spending time with him, while others remembered the odd meat he served that he claimed was deer from his hunting trips — though no one knew of Bar-Jonah to ever hunt.⁠
⁠
It was only after police had raided his bleach-scrubbed home and uncovered a list of 22 children's names and a meat grinder that they learned the grim truth about their 375-pound neighbor. Follow the link in our profile to learn more about Nathaniel Bar-Jonah's gruesome crimes.⁠
⁠
⁠
